6 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
7 132ND LEGISLATURE
8 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 747, L.D. 1128, “An Act to Modernize
10 the Formulary for Naturopathic Doctors”
11 Amend the bill by inserting after the title and before the enacting clause the following:
12 'Emergency preamble. Whereas, acts and resolves of the Legislature do not
13 become effective until 90 days after adjournment unless enacted as emergencies; and
14 Whereas, the rule designating the formulary for naturopathic doctors has not been
15 updated since 1996; and
16 Whereas, there is a statutory inconsistency that restricts the authority of the Board of
17 Complementary Health Care Providers to amend the formulary by rule; and
18 Whereas, this legislation corrects that inconsistency and must take effect immediately
19 so that the process to update the formulary can begin; and
20 Whereas, in the judgment of the Legislature, these facts create an emergency within
21 the meaning of the Constitution of Maine and require the following legislation as
22 immediately necessary for the preservation of the public peace, health and safety; now,
23 therefore,'
24 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
25 following:
26 'Sec. 1. 32 MRSA §12522, sub-§4, ¶B, as enacted by PL 1995, c. 671, §13, is
27 amended to read:
28 B. A naturopathic doctor may only prescribe noncontrolled legend drugs from the
29 following categories: homeopathic remedies, vitamins and minerals, hormones, local
30 anesthesia and immunizations that are designated by rule by a subcommittee of the
31 board consisting of the naturopathic members, the pharmacist member and the
32 allopathic or osteopathic physician member, as consistent with a naturopathic doctor's
33 education and training. A naturopathic doctor may not prescribe psychotropic
34 medications.
